		<a href="/conference_program/tracks_workshops/days.cfm?date=3">Thursday, May 15, 2003</a>
	
</p>

<p><b>Thursday, May 15, 2003</b></p>

	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="16"></a>1.4 - Take Your Game Online: Four Case Studies</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Online gaming is rapidly becoming one of the 
dominant forms of interactive entertainment. And 
as consoles link up via the web, a wide swath of 
consumers is being introduced to networked gaming 
and massively-multiplayer games. Are you prepared 
to develop an online title? What are the design, 
technical, and management challenges? What are 
the costs? The common pitfalls? The potential 
upside? This session will present case studies of 
four noteworthy online games. From development, 
to testing, through to launch, learn the basics 
of online game development from a panel of 
production and management professionals.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="22"></a>2.4 - Game Gems from Asia: More Influential Than You Think</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Most of us live and breathe the game industry as 
we know it in North America and Europe. But what 
about the Asian marketplace? Whether you view the 
region as one to sell in to, or one to comb for 
new ideas, it pays to know the current state of 
gaming in the Far East. From the sugary sweet 
love story genre, to quirky sims (some that deal 
with mundane tasks such as stocking a convenience 
store’s shelves), to a spike in MMOL titles 
geared toward young women, our panel will 
highlight the region’s most popular games and 
genres. In what ways is the Asian marketplace 
different than of ours, what new and creative 
games are due to enter their local markets, and 
what sort of influence can we expect those games 
to have here and around the globe?<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="30"></a>3.4 - Start-up Summit: How to Market Your Talent and Focus Your Business Strategy</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Changes to funding, development, distribution, 
and marketing means yesterday's start-up 
strategies may not work in the current market. 
This session will advise attendees how to 
structure a start-up development studio that 
takes advantage of current marketplace realities. 
Topics covered will include what publishers look 
for from development partners, how small- to mid-
size studios and businesses can take advantage of 
the outsourcing needs of larger, more traditional 
publishers and developers, how direct developer 
licensing deals work, the way work-for-hire deals 
are creating new opportunities for small-scale 
companies, and, in general, where opportunities 
exist for the smart and talented enterprise. 
Developers and content creators will walk away 
knowing how to position their business for 
success and how to give themselves the best 
chance at succeeding as an independent studio.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="36"></a>4.4 - Game AI Update: New Ways of Engaging the Player</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Game AI is revitalizing the game industry, but 
not for reasons you might expect. The renaissance 
in game AI isn’t coming from increased technical 
capabilities or more sophisticated programming 
tools alone, but from the simple fact that 
designers are using AI and scripting with goals 
of entertaining gamers in new ways. This session 
will look at games which use AI in unique ways 
(such as Black & White, Grand Theft Auto, and 
Deus Ex). Learn from our panel of AI programmers 
as they discuss how they implemented AI and 
scripting language in their current games, what 
the market is responding to, and how they plan on 
using AI in their upcoming titles.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="17"></a>1.5 - Survive the Platform Shakeout in Mobile Gaming</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Educate yourself on current adoption and usage 
figures associated with BREW, J2ME, 
SmartPhone2000, and other predominate mobile 
gaming platforms. Hear how SMS, EMS, WAP, MMS, 
and Voice are being enabled by carriers, and get 
an insider's view of how to choose among the 
differing platforms and languages in use today. 
Make the right platform choice for your unique 
game and for the market it is most likely to 
succeed in.

<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="23"></a>2.5 - Hot Shots: Learning from the Next Generation of Video Game Designers</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			This session will bring together a group of 
designers young enough, hungry enough, and smart 
enough to tackle new genres or push existing 
genres to new limits. Panelists will discuss 
lessons learned from their most recently-
completed project, where they stand in the 
progress on their current project, and what 
killer games they have planned for the future.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="31"></a>3.5 - Taking a Lesson from the Boom in Sports Sims</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			As a genre, sports sims drive the game industry. 
The genre not only outsells all others, its 
revenue for the past 5 years (through 2002) is 
trending to more than double, yet the games come 
in for very little scrutiny. This panel of top-
selling sports sim producers will discuss their 
methods, share their expertise, and discuss ways 
publishers and developers of other genres can 
learn from their acquired wisdom. Learn how 
intelligent use of licenses, a creative approach 
to sequels, having a structure that encourages 
and uses player feedback, and original (and 
sometimes over-the-top) marketing can drive huge 
revenues toward anyone’s bottom line.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="37"></a>4.5 - Tap the High-Tech Pulse of Gaming</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			Progress in ubiquitous gaming, adaptive audio, 
interactive music, and location-based games are 
just some areas where technology is influencing 
and sometimes changing the quality of game play. 
What is the status of these and other technical 
initiatives, in what ways are they changing game 
production and studio management, and is it time 
to address the technological challenge of 
transitioning to the next generation of consoles? 
Get up to speed on the most current high-tech 
development tools and learn how you can prepare 
your business enterprise for what lies ahead. <br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="18"></a>1.6 - Charting Change in Mobile Entertainment: For Survival and Success</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
			Room: 411<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			How has the mobile beat changed over the past 
year? What are the new strategies for success? 
How does a company target growth in this 
increasingly competitive space? This panel will 
look closely at the prevalent business models and 
trends operating in today's mobile game sector 
including current development costs, realistic 
funding scenarios, current revenue share and 
charge models, ways to break into foreign 
markets, growth patterns for handsets and PDA’s, 
and new opportunities to publish without a 
carrier deal in place. Increase your chances for 
success by understanding how the rules of mobile 
entertainment have changed.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="26"></a>2.6 - New Approaches to PR: The Modern Rules of Engagement</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
			Room: 404AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			What role does public relations play in your 
game’s or company’s overall marketing and 
branding campaigns? Competent PR is one of the 
most cost-effective ways of generating consumer 
and industry awareness for your product, but 
today’s important contacts extend far beyond the 
enthusiast press. In a world where the difference 
between five stars or one can spell success or 
failure at retail, understanding how the global 
press thinks, how game reviewers rate games, and 
how to reach them is essential.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="32"></a>3.6 -  Grow Your Career in the Game Industry</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
			Room: 406AB<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			As the games evolve, so do the skill sets 
required to maintain those games' high technical 
and creative standards. Understand the growing 
importance of skills including server 
engineering, digital effects and adaptive audio 
expertise, art skills outside of computer art 
(sculpture, painting, musical composition), and 
you are on your way to growing and solidifying 
your standing in the industry. Attendees will 
learn what skills are in demand now, and what 
skills will be required to support the onslaught 
of massively-multiplayer, console, mobile, PC and 
web games due in the coming years. <br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
		
		<p>	
		
			<b><a name="38"></a>4.6 - New Hooks in Gaming</b><br />
			Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
			Room: 408B<br />
			&nbsp;<br />
			What do The Sims, Grand Theft Auto, and Tony 
Hawk’s Pro Skater have in common? More than you 
think. Discover new ways game designers are using 
psychology, sociology, group dynamics, and 
artifacts of pop culture to make the new 
generation of games more appealing and rewarding 
to hardcore, casual, and neophyte gamers alike. 
Hear how the need for community, the power of 
freedom, and even the allure of rock ‘n’ roll are 
shaping a new generation of computer and video 
games.<br />
		
		</p>
			
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
		</table>
		
		
		
	
